on-arrival: advisor_action_timer = 6; last_advisor_action = 1; unity += 3; frente_unidad += 2; political_capital += 3; fac_renovadores += 2; pri_reformist_rel += 1

Verdugo's genius is not fire but glue. He spends the month in the least glamorous rooms in Mexican politics — the ones where four splinter parties argue about a comma in a joint declaration — and comes out with a comma they can all sign. Every fusion he brokers is a step toward the thing the left has never had and the state has always counted on it never having: a single house, with a single door, that the night of 1988 can knock on.
